Wash and dry produce.

Halve, peel, and dice @yellow onion{1}; thinly slice half the @jalapeño{1} into rounds; mince remaining jalapeño. TIP: Remove ribs and seeds first for less heat.

Heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{2%tsp} in a #medium pot{} (use a #large pot{} for 4 servings) over medium-high heat. Add onion and minced jalapeño; season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, stirring, until softened, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Add @ground turkey{10%ounce}, @Mexican spice blend{1%tbsp}, and @Southwest spice blend{1%tbsp} to pot; season with salt and pepper. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

> Swap in turkey or beef for pork.

Stir @tomato paste{1.5%ounce} into pot with pork mixture. Cook, stirring, until thoroughly combined, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add @diced tomatoes{14%ounce}, @black beans{1} and their liquid, @beef stock concentrate{1}, @water{1/4%cup}, salt, and pepper; stir to combine. Bring to a simmer and cook, uncovered, until thickened, ~{8-10%minutes}. Turn off heat. Taste and season with salt and pepper.

Divide chili between bowls. Top with @Monterey Jack cheese{1/4%cup}, @sour cream{1.5%tbsp}, and as much sliced jalapeño as you like. Serve.

> Ground Turkey is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.